ratings.question_text: What is your overall assessment of this course?

narratives.question_text: How would you summarize AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 for a fellow student? Would you recommend AFAM 505 01/AMST 643 01 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: This is a course that requires the absorption of an analytical system. If you are already familiar with that system, it may be easy, although it is still a fabulous opportunity to work through the scores of a very good quantity of music. I would highly recommend taking it. Seeing Professor Hepokoski in his element with this material, as well, is not to be missed.

A course that offers a good balance of literature coverage, analytical probing and methodological explorations. But if you really like Multivalence or have studied with James Webster don't take this course... just kidding.

narratives.question_text: How did this course deepen your knowledge of your discipline/profession? To what extent did this course contribute to your dissertation/research?
comments: Probably not relevant for dissertation, but I imagine that this will be very helpful for qualifying exams.

I feel much better prepared to tackle sonatas on my own now. That sounds like a silly and cliche thing to say in a course evaluation, but I mean it seriously. I think Hepokoski's elaboration of Sonata Theory is actually pretty brilliant.
